"Middleton, Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, Anglie","Braham, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1190–":"omkring 1190–Afdød","1190–Female":"1190–Afdød","1188–Male":"1188–Afdød","1217–1300":"1217–1300","1169–Male":"1169–Afdød","1169–Female":"1169–Afdød","1217":"1217","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1190":"omkring 1190","about 1217":"omkring 1217","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1300":"1300","1221":"1221","1188":"1188","1290":"1290","Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Jórvík, England","Middleton, Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Jórvík, England","Braham, Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1190–":"circa 1190–Overleden","1190–Female":"1190–Overleden","1188–Male":"1188–Overleden","1217–1300":"1217–1300","1169–Male":"1169–Overleden","1169–Female":"1169–Overleden","1217":"1217","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1190":"circa 1190","about 1217":"circa 1217","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1300":"1300","1221":"1221","1188":"1188","1290":"1290","Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Yorkshire, England","Middleton, Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, England","Braham, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1190–":"about 1190–Deceased","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1188–Male":"1188–Deceased","1217–1300":"1217–1300","1169–Male":"1169–Deceased","1169–Female":"1169–Deceased","1217":"1217","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1190":"about 1190","about 1217":"about 1217","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1300":"1300","1221":"1221","1188":"1188","1290":"1290","Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Yorkshire, England","Middleton, Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, England","Braham, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Braham in Spofforth (Yorkshire) or Brantham in Suffolk (recorded as <i>Braham</i> in 1198). Braham in Yorkshire was probably named with the Old English personal name <i>Brahha</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. Brantham in Suffolk means ‘the steep homestead’, from Old English <i>brant</i> ‘steep’ + <i>hām</i>.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’. Compare   Brain  .","Jewish: shortened form of   Abraham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brain","meanings":["English: apparently a nickname from Middle English <i>brain</i> ‘brain, mind’, probably short for <i>brainwod</i> ‘mad in the mind, furious’. Compare   Brainard  .","Irish (Down) and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b>, Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’, from <i>breitheamh</i> ‘judge’. Compare   Braham   2."]},{"name":"Bream","meanings":["English:","nickname for a fierce or energetic person, from Middle English <i>brem(e)</i>, <i>brim(me)</i> ‘fierce, vigorous’ (from Old English <i>brēme</i> ‘famous, noble’), or from a Middle English form of the Old English personal name <i>Brēme</i> with the same meaning.","variant of   Braham  ."]},{"name":"Brame","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Braham  .","German (also <b>Bräme</b>): variant of   Brahm   2. The surnames <i>Brame</i> and <i>Bräme</i> are very rare in Germany.","French: nickname from Old Occitan <i>brame</i> ‘cry, howl’."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":69,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":100,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Braham was born about 1190, in Yorkshire, England, her father, Hipotilitus de Braham, was 23 and her mother, Mrs. Hipotilitus de Braham, was 22. She married Arthur Westwick in 1221. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Middleton, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1190–":"umbes 1190–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1188–Male":"1188–Surnud","1217–1300":"1217–1300","1169–Male":"1169–Surnud","1169–Female":"1169–Surnud","1217":"1217","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1190":"umbes 1190","about 1217":"umbes 1217","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1300":"1300","1221":"1221","1188":"1188","1290":"1290","Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Yorkshire, England","Middleton, Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, England","Braham, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1190–":"noin 1190–Kuollut","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1188–Male":"1188–Kuollut","1217–1300":"1217–1300","1169–Male":"1169–Kuollut","1169–Female":"1169–Kuollut","1217":"1217","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1190":"noin 1190","about 1217":"noin 1217","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1300":"1300","1221":"1221","1188":"1188","1290":"1290","Craven, Yorkshire, England":"Craven, Yorkshire, England","Middleton, Yorkshire, England":"Middleton, Yorkshire, England","Braham, Yorkshire, England